The applicant may be entitled to make a claim for relief: 
r 5.3(1)(a)
;

The applicant has made reasonable enquiries: 
r 5.3(1)(a)
;

Notwithstanding the reasonable enquiries, the applicant has been unable to obtain sufficient information to decide whether or not to commence proceedings against the prospective defendant: 
r 5.3(1)(a)
;

The prospective defendant may have a document or thing that could assist in determining whether the applicant is entitled to make a claim for relief: 
r 5.3(2)
;

Preliminary discovery applications may not always be the subject of a contest to which the ordinary “follow the event” costs rule (see UCPR 
r 42.1
) properly applies: Totalise plc v Motley Fool Ltd [2001] All ER (D) 290 (Dec); [2003] 2 All ER 872; [2002] 1 WLR 1233 . In some cases it is merely a matter for the moving party to establish their entitlement to the order, in much the same way as a successful applicant for leave to amend or for leave to extend a limitation period — and against whom costs may be awarded: see [42.1.25]. For example, if the person against whom preliminary discovery is sought holds the documents subject to an obligation of confidence that has been reasonably incurred, it will often be appropriate to order the successful discovery applicant to pay the costs: Norwich Pharmacal Co v Customs and Excise Cmrs [1974] AC 133; [1973] 2 All ER 943; [1973] 3 WLR 164 ); Bio Transplant Inc v Bell Potter Securities Ltd [2008] NSWSC 694;  BC200805343  (plaintiff to pay defendants costs of application and compliance — defendant co-operated but refused to disclose identity of the client based on confidentiality arrangements — justified in wanting to be compelled by the court to make discovery to which it resisted). In this sense, where there are potentially conflicting considerations in relation to disclosure a defendant to a discovery application may be in a “difficult” position: Airways Corporation of New Zealand v Koenig [2002] NSWSC 521;  BC200203174 . If an application for preliminary discovery is in fact contested in an adversarial fashion then the ordinary cost consequences should apply: Steffen v Australia and New Zealand Banking Group Ltd [2009] NSWSC 883;  BC200907907 at [29], [32]–[38]  (proceedings on application for preliminary discovery characterised as adversarial — costs follow the event in accordance with 
r 42.1
); Airways Corporation of New Zealand v Koenig t/a Pricewaterhouse Coopers Legal [2002] NSWSC 521;  BC200203174  (proceedings were “akin to adversarial litigation” — costs follow the event); Panasonic Australia Pty Ltd v Ngage Pty Ltd (No 2) [2006] NSWSC 399;  BC200603145  (if there is a contested application then costs follow the event).

